'''Bridge therapy''' is [[therapy]] intended, in transportation [[metaphor]], to serve as a [[figurative analogy|figurative]] bridge to another stage of therapy or health, carrying a [[patient]] past a challenging period of some kind. There are various types of bridge therapy, such as bridge to transplant, bridge to candidacy, bridge to decision, bridge to recovery, and anticoagulation bridge (such as heparin bridge). Bridge therapy exists in contrast to [[destination therapy]], which is the figurative destination rather than a bridge to something else. * '''Bridge to transplant''': Such therapy preserves someone's health well enough and long enough that they can make it to [[organ transplantation|organ transplant]], still being [[organ transplantation#Allocation of organs|eligible for transplant]] after spending time waiting for an organ to become available. For example, [[left ventricular assist device|LVAD]] often serves as a bridge to [[heart transplantation|heart transplant]],<ref name="pmid_28504892">{{Citation |last=Nakagawa |first=S |display-authors=etal |year=2017 |title=Palliative care interventions before left ventricular assist device implantation in both bridge to transplant and destination therapy |journal=J Palliat Med |volume= |issue= |pmid=28504892 |pmc=4125758 |doi=10.1089/jpm.2016.0568 |postscript=.}}</ref> locoregional therapy (such as [[radiofrequency ablation]]) for [[hepatocellular carcinoma]] can serve as a bridge to [[liver transplantation|liver transplant]],<ref name="pmid_25099448">{{Citation |last=Prasad |first=MA |last2=Kulik |first2=LM |year=2014 |title=The role of bridge therapy prior to orthotopic liver transplantation |journal=J Natl Compr Canc Netw |volume=12 |issue=8 |pages=1183–1190; quiz 1191 |url=http://www.jnccn.org/content/12/8/1183.long |pmid=25099448 |postscript=.}}</ref> and [[lung volume reduction surgery|LVRS]] can serve as a bridge to [[lung transplantation|lung transplant]].<ref name="pmid_14720034">{{Citation |last=Cordova |first=FC |last2=Criner |first2=GJ |year=2002 |title=Lung volume reduction surgery as a bridge to lung transplantation |journal=Am J Respir Med |volume=1 |issue=5 |pages=313–324 |url= |pmid=14720034 |pmc= |doi= |postscript=.}}</ref><ref name="pmid_23736352">{{Citation |last=Shigemura |first=N |display-authors=etal |year=2013 |title=Lung transplantation after lung volume reduction surgery |journal=Transplantation |volume=96 |issue=4 |pages=421–425 |url= |pmid=23736352 |doi=10.1097/TP.0b013e31829853ac |postscript=.}}</ref> * '''Bridge to candidacy''': A patient was too sick to be a candidate for a certain therapy, but the bridge carries them to a state of being eligible; for example, [[extracorporeal membrane oxygenation|ECMO]] as a bridge to nontransplant [[cardiac surgery]].<ref name="pmid_28672423">{{Citation |last=Wallinder |first=A |last2=Pellegrino |first2=V |last3=Fraser |first3=JF |last4=McGiffin |first4=DC |year=2017 |title=ECMO as a bridge to non-transplant cardiac surgery |journal=J Card Surg |volume= |issue= |pmid=28672423 |doi=10.1111/jocs.13172 |postscript=.}}</ref> * '''Bridge to decision''': A decision will soon be made about what to do next (that is, which [[definitive therapy]] will come soon), but first the patient needs a bridge to support them until that decision; for example, short-term mechanical circulatory support as a bridge to durable [[ventricular assist device|left ventricular assist device]] implant in refractory [[cardiogenic shock]].<ref name="pmid_28472406">{{Citation |last=den Uil |first=CA |display-authors=etal |year=2017 |title=Short-term mechanical circulatory support as a bridge to durable left ventricular assist device implantation in refractory cardiogenic shock: a systematic review and meta-analysis |journal=Eur J Cardiothorac Surg |volume= |issue= |pmid=28472406 |doi=10.1093/ejcts/ezx088 |postscript=.}}</ref> * '''Bridge to recovery''': A recovery is likely, but first support is needed to carry someone through a tough time; for example, [[extracorporeal membrane oxygenation|ECMO]] in [[methamphetamine]] toxicity, which can be viewed as both [[salvage therapy|rescue therapy]] and bridge to recovery.<ref name="pmid_28758605">{{Citation |last=Morrison |first=LK |display-authors=etal |year=2017 |title=Rescue extracorporeal membrane oxygenation therapy in methamphetamine toxicity |journal=CJEM |volume= |issue= |pmid=28758605 |doi=10.1017/cem.2017.356 |postscript=.}}</ref> * '''Anticoagulation bridge''': Temporary [[anticoagulation]], such as with [[heparin]], is used during a [[perioperative]] period when a patient's regular anticoagulant therapy, such as with [[warfarin]], is suspended;<ref name="Medscape_Periop_anticoag">{{Citation |last=Daley |first=Brian J. |last2=Taylor |first2=Dana |last3=Aycinena Goicolea |first3=Jose Fernando |editor-last=Schwer |editor-first=William A. |date=2016-03-28 |title=Perioperative anticoagulation management |work=Medscape |url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/285265-overview |access-date=2017-08-11 |postscript=.}}</ref><ref name="pmid_25126354">{{Citation |last=Baser |first=Onur |last2=Supina |first2=Dylan |last3=Sengupta |first3=Nishan |last4=Wang |first4=Li |year=2011 |title=Anticoagulation bridging therapy patterns in patients undergoing total hip or total knee replacement in a US health plan: real-world observations and implications |journal=Am Health Drug Benefits |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=240–248 |pmid=25126354 |pmc=4125758 |postscript=.}}</ref> the goal is to prevent excess risk of severe [[bleeding]] during or after surgery. The heparin bridge provides some anticoagulant effect (to prevent [[thrombosis]] from warfarin withdrawal) but not as much as would make severe bleeding likely.
