'''''Dar al-Hikma''''' ({{lang-ar|دار الحكمة}}, 'House of Wisdom') was an underground publishing house, set up by the [[Iraqi Communist Party]] in September 1945.<ref name="Thompson2013">{{cite book|author=Elizabeth F. Thompson|title=Justice Interrupted|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=39QuUZQhsbsC&pg=PT181|date=15 April 2013|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-07619-8|page=181}}</ref> It published literature on politics, science, economy and culture.<ref name="Thompson2013"/> It issues Arabic translations on [[Friedrich Engels]]' ''[[Origin of the Family]]'', [[Maxim Gorky]]'s ''[[The Mother (1906 novel)|Mother]]'' and texts of [[Stalin]] on [[dialectics]] and [[historical materialism]]. The main source for the literature published was English-language books brought from the [[Soviet Union]]. Party members working with bookstores in [[Baghdad]] and [[Amarah]] enabled the sales of the books.<ref name="Bashkin">{{cite book|author=Orit Bashkin|title=The Other Iraq: Pluralism and Culture in Hashemite Iraq|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WRH16rEBLKQC&pg=PA75|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-7415-4|page=75}}</ref> Dar al-Hikma was financed by contributions from party members, the party managed to gather 6,000 [[Iraqi dinar]]s for the purpose.<ref name="Thompson2013"/> Dar al-Hikma had a short life-span.<ref name="Fernea1991">{{cite book|author=Robert Alan Fernea|title=The Iraqi revolution of 1958: the old social classes revisited|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kvANAQAAMAAJ|year=1991|publisher=Tauris|isbn=978-1-85043-318-7|page=176}}</ref>

