{{Infobox NRHP | name = Silkville | nrhp_type = | image = Silkville School.jpg | caption = Silkville's school house | location = [[Williamsburg Township, Franklin County, Kansas|Williamsburg Township]], [[Franklin County, Kansas]] | nearest_city= [[Williamsburg, Kansas]] | coordinates = {{coord|38|27|00|N|95|29|21|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Kansas | built = 1870 | architecture = | added = December 15, 1972 | area = {{convert|6|acre}} | governing_body = Private | refnum = 72000504 }}
'''Silkville''' is a [[ghost town]] in [[Williamsburg Township, Franklin County, Kansas]], United States. Its elevation is 1,161&nbsp;feet (354&nbsp;m), and it is located at {{coord|38|27|0|N|95|29|21|W|type:city}} (38.4500149, -95.4891477),<ref>{{gnis|484824}} [[United States Geological Survey]]. Retrieved September 28, 2015.</ref> along [[U.S. Route 50 in Kansas|U.S. Route 50]] southwest of [[Williamsburg, Kansas|Williamsburg]].<ref>[[#KAG|''Kansas Atlas & Gazetteer'' (2009)]], p. 52.</ref>
The settlement was founded in the late 1800s by a Frenchman named Ernest de Boissière, who believed in [[Charles Fourier|Fourierian]] [[utopian socialism]]. Silkville was a [[sericulture]]-based settlement, and [[remuneration]] was based what each settler could produce. Silkville's silk was praised at the [[Centennial Exposition]] in [[Philadelphia]] in 1876, but loss of settlers and difficulty in selling the silk resulted in the settlements collapse. Today, only a few buildings remain.
==History==
Silkville was established in 1870 by a Frenchman named Ernest de Boissière. Born in 1810 in France to a noble family, Boissière espoused radical political opinions heavily inspired by the [[Fourierism|specific socialist philosophy]] of [[Charles Fourier]], which became anathematic when the authoritarian [[Napoleon III]] [[French coup d'état of 1851|consolidated power in 1851]]. Consequently, Boissière was forced into exile and moved to America, where he first settled in the port city of [[New Orleans]].<ref name=register>[[#Pankratz|Pankratz (1972)]], p. 2.</ref><ref name=tollefson80>[[#Tollefson|Tollefson (2015)]], p. 80.</ref> In this new city, he set up a [[shipping line]]. However, because he poured some of his money into supporting orphaned black children, he garnered heavy criticism from wealthy whites; desiring to escape the hostile opinions of his neighbors, Boissière was left with no choice but to leave the [[Southern United States|American South]].<ref name=tollefson80/><ref name=silk67>[[#Fitzgerald|Fitzgerald (1988)]], p. 67.</ref> He then decided to move to [[Franklin County, Kansas]], an area he believed was well-suited to the establishment of a [[Utopia|utopic]] community. In 1869, Boissière purchased between 3000 and 3500 acres of land in the county from the Kansas Educational Association of the Methodist Episcopal Church and went about setting up his [[Commune|intentional settlement]].<ref name=register/><ref name=tollefson80/>
[[Image:SilkvilleSchool1884.png|thumb|left|An 1884 photograph, showing students and teachers gathered at the Silkville school house.]]
After operating under myriad names, including Kansas Cooperative Farm, Prairie Home, and Valeton, Boissière's colony came to be known as Silkville, as it was intended to be a Fourierian commune that survived via [[Sericulture|silk production]].<ref name=register/><ref name=tour/> The first building that Boissière constructed was a massive abode that others in the area referred to simply as the "Chateau".<ref name=silk67/><ref>[[#Pankratz|Pankratz (1972)]], p. 3.</ref> For a time the largest manor in the state, this house boasted sixty-rooms that could comfortably hold between 50{{en dash}}100 people. The building was also home to a huge library filled with 2,500 books, tomes, and other volumes.<ref name=silk67/> Boissière also erected a stone cocoonery and planted thousands of [[mulberry trees]] to feed his silkworms.<ref name=register/><ref name=tour>{{cite web|last1=Richards|last2=Barker|first1=Catherine Jane|first2=Deborah|title=Southwest Franklin County|url=http://www.franklincokshistory.org/places-2/tours/southwest-franklin-county/|publisher=Franklin County Historical Society|accessdate=March 22, 2015}}</ref> These groves were later joined by hundreds of peach, apple and [[Ailanthus|ailanthus]] trees, as well as over a thousand grape vines.<ref name=silk68>[[#Fitzgerald|Fitzgerald (1988)]], p. 68.</ref> To educate the children of the colony, Boissière established a school that, according to author and historian Daniel Fitzgerald, was "the first in Kansas in which the instructors attempted to teach the contemporary world literature of the day".<ref name=silk67/>
Boissière structured his colony so that [[remuneration]] was based what each settler could produce, thereby rewarding the efficient labor of assiduous workers. Upon its founding, 40 French emigrants settled at the colony, each paying 100 dollars to be a part of the commune.<ref name=register/><ref name=tollefson80/><ref name=silk67/> In 1875, Charles Sears, a friend of Boissière's, moved to Silkville, and his arrival was a boon for the settlement's sericulture. The following year, Boissière's silk was lauded at the [[Centennial Exposition]] in [[Philadelphia]]. Despite this critical reception, Silkville struggled to make money, largely because it was competing with comparatively cheaper fabrics imported from Asia, and because Boissière refused to use cost-effective American dyes.<ref name=tollefson83>[[#Tollefson|Tollefson (2015)]], p. 83.</ref> Over the years, many members left.<ref name=register/> (Most, when they had arrived in America, spoke only French but soon learned English and began to assimilate into mainstream society.) Many immigrants also learned that for 100 dollars{{em dash}}the amount that they had pledged to live in the settlement{{em dash}}they could buy their own land.<ref name=tollefson84>[[#Tollefson|Tollefson (2015)]], p. 84.</ref> To compensate, Boissière shifted production towards butter, cheese, and the raising of livestock. While this kept the settlement afloat for a few years, Silkville eventually collapsed and its members dispersed.<ref name=nomination/> Boissière returned to France in 1892 (dying two years later), and his property was given to the [[Independent Order of Odd Fellows]] for use as an orphanage. Financial reasons compelled the Order to give up the property, and after a long court battle, it passed into the hands of lawyers from Topeka. In 1916, a fire hollowed out the "Chateau", only part of which was ever reconstructed.<ref name=nomination>[[#Pankratz|Pankratz (1972)]], pp. 3, 5.</ref><ref name=silk70>[[#Fitzgerald|Fitzgerald (1988)]], p. 70.</ref>
==Remains== [[Image:Silkville sign.jpg|thumb|Today, the Silkville Ranch exists upon the former settlement.]] Today, little remains of Silkville, and only three stone structures survive: the settlement's school house, and two barns.<ref name=register/> The original chateau that Boissiere constructed{{em dash}}which, at the time of its construction cost US$10,000{{em dash}}was destroyed in the aforementioned fire, and a modern home was built over the west end of the ruin, utilizing some of the stone from the original.<ref name=nomination2>[[#Pankratz|Pankratz (1972)]], pp. 2–3.</ref> One of the modern day barns was once the settlement's cocoonery, although it was reduced to a one-level building after a tornado damaged the top floor.<ref name=tollefson84/> In 1972, these buildings were added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] because of their significance in the [[history of Kansas]].<ref name=nris >{{cite web|title=Silkville|url=http://focus.nps.gov/AssetDetail/NRIS/72000504|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref> The aspects of the community seen as most significant historically were its nature as an [[intentional community]] and its practice of [[sericulture]].<ref>[[#Pankratz|Pankratz (1972)]], p. 5.</ref>
